EDGE: The NFL Play Recommendation System¶

The goal for this project is to create a Recommender System that can determine the best play call given specific situations to maximize a teams chance of adding points (EPA), while also being user-friendly.

First things first What Is EPA?

Expected Points Added (EPA) is a statistic used to gauge the value of a play and is the main statistic that the NFL uses these days. Expected Points (EP) is used to gauge the states of a play. Expected Points takes into account the Down, how many yards until First down (yards to go), how much time left in the half, and field position. This equation is based off of every single play in NFL history and is recalculated after every week.

Data Clean Up¶

To give our model as many scenarios as possible, data of every snap, from every game, for the last decade of games were aggregated. Together the data begins with Bears vs Packers in 2019 and ends with Seattle vs ST Louis Rams.

Here general data clean up is completed, that includes creating our success column which is a binary column of good/bad EPA. The criterion for success was determined as any play greater than 0 EPA was deemed a success and negative play was unsuccessful. A new feature engineereed was creating the different concepts from previous columns that specify where the ball ended up going. (The Data courtesy of NFLScrapR)

The different concepts are as follows: Runs (left or right) off of different Offensive Lineman. Tight end, Tackles and Guards. Passes (left or right) based on distance. Short passes are anything 15 yards and less, while deep passes are 15 yards and longer.

Decision Tree¶

A regression decision tree was at first to predict a given EPA based on situational football. Decision Trees are supervised machine learning model that use past data to predict new data. They break down the data by making a decision based on rules or "asking questions of our model" used to predicts a target. In our case its EPA on a given play.

After breaking down the model it has to be validated to see what the scores are and determine the accuracy of it. This is done by splitting the data before hand into training and testing features, once the model is run on the training features, we use a predict function and compare those answers to the actual (test) results. In this case our predicted values seem slightly off from the actual but we can run tests to specifically find out by how much.

In [160]:
from sklearn import metrics
print('Mean Absolute Error:', round(metrics.mean_absolute_error(play_target_test_m2, Y_pred2),2))
print('Mean Squared Error:', round(metrics.mean_squared_error(play_target_test_m2, Y_pred2),2))
print('Root Mean Squared Error:', np.sqrt(round(metrics.mean_squared_error(play_target_test_m2, Y_pred2),2)))

Mean Absolute Error: 0.61
Mean Squared Error: 1.43
Root Mean Squared Error: 1.1958260743101399

Mean Absolute Error is the most significant value in this case and it shows the results of our predicted values vs the actual values. So on average our model was off by 0.61 EPA. Ideally the perfect model is closer to 0 but we will implement a random forest regressor to get a better prediction.

Mean squared error and RMSE are more useful when worried about outliers but for the scope of this project that does not concern us.

Random Forest¶

With that high of error, we can try to find ways to fine tune and improve the model. The most basic way is to run a random forest module. Random Forests are an ensemble of decision trees used to find the best accuracy of the model, called "bagging".

In [182]:
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor

rfregressor = RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=20, random_state=0)
rfregressor.fit(matrix_train, target_train)
y_pred = rfregressor.predict(matrix_test)

Mean Absolute Error: 0.48
Mean Squared Error: 0.76
Root Mean Squared Error: 0.8717797887081347

Random forest yields an improvement in all 3 values, our model now is off by less than .5 EPA points and this seems more acceptable to predict plays with.

To make the Play Predictor Model it uses the EPA values, along with inputs from the user on situations such as Yardline, Down, Distance, Score Differential, Timeouts left and Quarter. The goal is to predict the play concept such as short pass right, run left tackle, deep pass middle etc with the highest EPA (chance of scoring) possible. When used in practice it can give a team an idea of which concepts to call based on the 10 years of data used to make a decision. Once the values from the user have been inputted the model runs through multiple scenarios of different play calls along with whether or not they are successful or not. The ouput displays a ranked order of the best play to call for the situation.

Play Recommender System¶

To create the recommendation system, several random forest models were aggregated based on the inputted situations and modifying each iteration for success =1 or success = 0. Each concept was iterated through to find the EPA that would be produced given the situation provided by the user. The difference between the successful and unsuccessful plays were aggregated into a dataframe to give a simple view of the all the options and what the outcomes could potentially be.

def graph(epa, concept, df):
    a4_dims = (11.7, 8.27)
    fig, ax = pyplot.subplots(figsize=a4_dims)

In that scenario Head Coach Pete Carroll called a slant to the right (short right pass) which was intercepted by Patriots defender Malcom Butler and led to the Patriots winning the Super Bowl. In that same scenario this model predicts that passes to the right are not ideal and runs to the right side would result in lower chances of scoring. Meanwhile passing to the back left or back middle of the endzone are the optimal choices or a short pass to the left side. Running off the left and right guard are not terrible choices as they increase the chance to score slightly.
